       The  notion of the ``current process'' is muddy.  The cur-
       rent algorithm is `the highest  numbered  process  on  the
       terminal  that is not ignoring interrupts, or, if there is
       none, the highest numbered process on the terminal'.  This
       fails,  for example, in critical sections of programs like
       the shell and editor, or when faulty programs  running  in
       the  background  fork  and  fail to ignore interrupts.  In
       cases where no process can be found, w prints -.

       The CPU time is only an estimate, in particular, if  some-
       one leaves a background process running after logging out,
       the person currently on that terminal is ``charged''  with
       the time.

       Background  processes  are  not  shown,  even  though they
       account for much of the load on the system.

